# Ecosystem mapping

![](data:image/png;base64,)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Overview
Ecosystem mapping is a visual tool used to understand the complex network of actors, organizations, and influences surrounding a particular issue or innovation. It focuses on the interconnectedness of these elements.

## Purpose
The purpose of ecosystem mapping is to provide a holistic view of the ecosystem, helping to identify opportunities, potential collaborators, and potential risks to R&D efforts. It facilitates understanding how changes in one part of the ecosystem affect others.

## How it works
Ecosystem mapping involves defining the scope of the innovation or problem, identifying actors within the ecosystem, mapping relationships between them, and showing value flows between different actors. This process helps to unveil hidden opportunities, foster collaboration, and future-proof R&D strategies.

## Requirements
To effectively use ecosystem mapping for R&D, one needs domain expertise, stakeholder information, collaboration tools, systems thinking, facilitation skills, openness to new ideas, and an iterative mindset.

## Reflections
When using ecosystem mapping for R&D purposes, it's essential to maintain a clear focus on the innovation or problem being addressed, balance depth and breadth in the map, and regularly update the map based on new information and developments. Actionable insights should be derived from the map to inform strategic decisions.

## Related methods (if any)
Ecosystem mapping is related to Co-creation, Human-Centered Design, Crowdsourcing, Horizon Scanning, and Visual Thinking & Mapping.

## Examples
Two examples of ecosystem mapping are described: one as a visual tool that helps understand the complex network of actors and influences surrounding an innovation, and another as a dynamic map built to provide a rich database, crowdsourced, with catalysing action in mind.
